## Why This Is Asked
Evaluate hands-on ability to translate policy into Gatekeeper and Kyverno, using SPIFFE for workload identity and enforcing data-scoping in a real multi-tenant setup.

## Key Concepts
- Gatekeeper ConstraintTemplate and Constraint
- Kyverno policy enforcement
- SPIFFE IDs for notebook workloads
- Data catalog whitelisting and kernel/runtime controls

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-check illustrating the policy guard
function isCompliant(pod) {
  const spiffe = pod?.metadata?.annotations?.['spiffe.io/id'];
  const mounts = (pod?.spec?.containers?.[0]?.volumeMounts || [])
    .map(m => m.mountPath);
  const hasWhitelistedData = mounts.some(p => p.startsWith('/data/whitelist'));
  const hasApprovedKernel = !!spiffe && spiffe.startsWith('spiffe://')
    && (pod?.spec?.containers?.[0]?.image || '').includes('approved-runtime');
  return hasWhitelistedData && hasApprovedKernel;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you validate policy effectiveness in CI/CD and in prod?
- How would you handle exceptions for legitimate data-science projects without widening risk?

